segments.text: Petroleum engineering, all my dad could see of that was more oil patch.
And my brother was successful as a petroleum engineering student and went to work for the old Humble Oil Pipeline Exxon.
And then when I let dad know I wanted to go to A&M, he was very much for that.
And he and mother made a lot of sacrifices.
trying to save up money to assist us in coming to A&M.
But I had worked some and had tried to save up money, and I had the valedictorian scholarship.
How much was it then?
Oh, goodness.
It paid your basic tuition, and that's all it paid.
I think tuition was $250 a semester back then.
It was not much, but it was, it helped, I can assure you that.
But as far as spending money, no, it was fairly frugal.
And I, you know, most of the other fish were pretty much in the same.
And how often did you contact parents?
Writing or phone calls?
You know, as much as I could.
I had...
I had become a ham radio operator in high school.
And W5AC, the old radio station at A&M, Ham Radio Club, I joined the, and that was one of the things that you,
It's where you could get away from the other things.
You could belong to the committees over at the MSC and the student groups.
And I became a member of the ham radio club.
And I could talk to a ham in Atlanta, which is 13 miles up above McLeod, and all on the same telephone exchange.
And I could call this ham in Atlanta, and they'd phone patch me down to my mom and my dad.
They were on a party line, but we usually could get through.
And so a couple times a week, I talked to home via ham radio on a phone patch.
And did you write very much, or was primary?
Yes, no, we wrote, wrote a lot.
My two precious sisters kept me going.
They wrote religiously, wanting to know what was happening to baby brother and what he was doing.
Did you drive home before Thanksgiving?
Haskell, one time illegally.
We're not supposed to go.
The weekend of the Fort Worth Corps trip, TCU, Jim Stewart, who was a senior civilian, okay, he was a civilian student in civil engineering.
And Jim and I decided to make an excursion through McLeod to go by home just real quickly and maybe even find a girl or two to take to Fort Worth with us.
And we had a car wreck.
And no real serious injury.
Oh, I complained of a little bit of a back problem for a while, but... Wasn't that Studebaker?
No, no.
Jim was driving.
He was a senior, and his folks were...
fairly well off.
And Jim was driving a fairly new 59 Ford Galaxy.
And we were driving from McLeod going to go back up through

uh... the Atlanta area known to uh... to finish up our trip and then we had the wreck and of course then we got caught because I spent a couple of days uh... in the hospital and uh... had to call back the A&M and say goodbye.
What kind of punishment did you get in the outfit?
They were uh... they were sympathetic to the extent that uh...
I uh...
I came back a little bit uh... bunged up and what have you and uh...
They did not really want to take advantage of the situation of coming down on me too hard.
They let me know that I had done something that I was not supposed to do.
Did you make the other Corps trip that year?
Austin or Houston?
Haskell, I think maybe it was Rice.
I don't remember exactly.
Yes, I made the Corps trip, sure did.
On a typical Corps trip, where did you and your buddies stay?
As freshmen?
Particularly as freshmen.
Like if you went to Houston, do you remember where you stayed?
In Houston, I would stay.
I had a...
By that time, I had a sister in Houston, in fact, in Houston, and I would stay with her.
And there was not a lot of staying because, you know, you went to the game and maybe you could spend that one night and then you had to be back in before quarter quarters the next day.
And so there was not a lot that went on, really.
How, on court trips all of your years,
How were Aggies treated during the march and so forth by the typical spectators?
Oh, gosh, Haskell, they came out by the thousands and lined the streets and hollered at you and applauded, and the old band go by, and people would just go bananas.
It was no shouting, ridicule, or anything like that.
Aggies were treated with
Oh, I thought utmost respect on those Corps trips.
I thought we were kind of treated special.
Gosh, the Aggies are coming to town.
Let's fall out for them.
Let's line the streets for them.
Oh, I can remember photographs of those Corps trips and seeing those.
And my brain has just gone to sleep.
I hadn't thought about this.
When did Corps trips stop?
I don't remember.
Do you?
When they stopped?
I don't know that they ever stopped.
Well, did they go on until the Southwest Conference was terminated about 10 years ago?
I don't even know.
Maybe they don't have any court trips now, none at all.
That has, I've gone to sleep.
That's passed me by.
With SMU, TCU, and Rice gone.
Yeah, where do you go for?
The only other would be UT or Baylor.
And the Baylor stopped.
I don't know Haskell.
In all of the interviews, I have not gotten any negative on court trips.
No, it was fun, and we were treated with tremendous respect.
And I was also in the singing cadets.
As a fish?
No, I started singing cadets my second semester of my sophomore year.
We'll get to that in a second.
Yeah.
During that freshman year, you went to Yale practice.
Oh, yes.
Was it midnight, or was it earlier in the Grove?
It was in the Grove, and it was right after chow, the best I remember.
Haskell, I think it was just right after chow, and it was at the Grove.
How did people behave?
Oh...
rowdy, a lot of hollering, but no foul language to speak of, and no drinking.
Did they tell fables?
Oh, goodness, yes.
And they were halfway clean fables.
I mean, they would imply some impropriety, but nothing just real bad.
Oh, no, I remember those well, yeah.
Then
No worse than the Jody calls that we had marching around camp.
Well, we had Jody calls, and we'd get called down every once in a while.
The Bulls would send word down no more of those Jody calls, you know.
Did you all have a rival outfit, core outfit, that you were always kind of competing with, playing?
Haskell, I guess every one in what was called the second...
brigade over there, you know, A-2, B-2, C-2, D-2, E-2, F-2, G-2, and the H-1 was real screwing that it was assigned to that second brigade.
It never was.
It was always assigned to second brigade.
I guess there was some competition, especially for precision in marching and those sort of things, but it seemed like most people wanted to do things over at Henderson Hall where the jocks were.
You wanted to go over to Henderson Hall and put ink in the swimming pool or whatever you could do to kind of shake those guys up.
Did you ever get caught in any kind of a prank and get a punishment?
Like putting some ink in or caught a Babbo bomb?
I was involved in a couple of drown outs in one Babbo bomb incident.
And what?
That was not caught on any of them and denied any involvement.
Used somebody else's trash can on the drown out, you know, instead of using your own.
It wasn't smart to use your own.
It traced you back to where it came from.
Only two things that I thought were questionable.
Charlie Rollins, our first sergeant, there was a junior Yale leader.
I want to say that boy's name was Sonny Todd.
I can't remember his name.
Maybe it was Sonny Todd.
We were told to...
If we ever had a chance to catch Sonny Todd to take a mattress cover, you know, our bedding, our mattresses, we were furnished by the Corps a mattress cover.
And to take him and put him in that mattress cover and tie it up good and put him four or five feet up the flagpole.
And we did that.
And it didn't hurt the guy, but he didn't know exactly how high he was off the ground.
He did not want to flounce around too much.
I think that happened in the first water fight we had as a fish.
The second water fight is probably the one where I made a dumb mistake.
In retrospect, it didn't really hurt anybody.
And as a more mature student, I would not have done it and certainly would not advise anyone to do it.
But in our second water fight, my fishy old lady and I, we were chasing, I believe, this same EL leader who Charlie wanted us to get again.
And he ran to the door of the guard room at the end of dorm 14.
and was able to get into the guard room before we could get any water on him.
And I turned around and there was a bull, Colonel Scott.
And Colonel Scott was called the Goose.
That was his nickname, the Goose.
I turned around and the Goose was almost face to face with me and I poured water on him.
And ran and went around and came in the side door 14.
And Charlie Rollins hid me in his closet while the goose went up and down every hallway in 14, 15, 16, trying to find who it was pouring water on him.
And I could pass Colonel Scott on the sidewalk, and I would very...
I would salute him, and it was, good morning, sir, good afternoon, sir.
And I know that he would say, I've seen that fish somewhere before.
That probably was as much a... You never got caught on that one?
Never got caught on that one.
No one told.
Rollins didn't tell.
All right, on a serious side of Good Bull, were you and some of your buddies ever involved in a prank which now in hindsight you realize was dangerous?
Yeah, we threw M-80s when we weren't supposed to throw M-80s, could have blown hands off and blown toes off, a lot of things.
I was present when M-80s were flushed down the crappers.
That could have, you know, you could have hurt people doing those sort of things.
I tried to put a guy up a flagpole, you know, even though it might not have been four or five feet was probably not the best judgment in the world to use, but we did it.
Describe you and your buddy's role in Bonfire your freshman year.
I had it made.
My buddies worked their tails off, and their whole job, of course, was just to carry logs out.
That's all they got to do.
I stayed on the radio the whole time because I was a ham radio operator, and I was in the communication tent from day one to day in.
About how long did bonfire preparation take?
Oh, I don't remember it being more than a month.
I would think more in terms of two to three weeks, maybe.
And where was the cut area?
Do you remember?
Oh, no, I really don't.
I could not even begin to tell you where the cut area was then.
It was still on the drill field.
Still on the drill field.
How did you feel when you saw that fire?
Oh, it was amazing.
I mean, just magnificent.
You know, it was...
I did not associate it so much with that desire to beat out of TU.
I didn't associate it with that near as much as I did, my goodness, look what we've put together and look what we're doing.
Yeah, it made a lasting impression on me and will never forget my first one.
So when you go home,
Christmas that first year.
Are you feeling pretty good about being an Aggie?
Haskell, I was when I got home.
And the toughest time of my life, until today, was the Christmas break of my fifth year.
I had had that little accident, and like I say, it didn't slow me down much.
Got through bonfire because I was in communications anyway.
I got home, and you know, back in those days, you came back after
Christmas to take final exams.
And they had about a week of class, maybe two weeks of class after Christmas, and then a week of final exams.
And I thought I was reasonably prepared to come back and finish up the semester.
And like I would say, I was just an average student.
I was making B's and C's and not really tearing anything up.
But I got home and
No sweetheart or anything else involved.
I just got home, and home looked so good.
And, you know, Mom and Dad looked so good.
My youngest sister, I mean, those things, it was just so emotional to go home.

and really spend some time, because that was essentially about it, you know, I, I, it seemed like we did go home, uh, I can't even remember, I don't even think I went home Thanksgiving, I, it seemed like maybe, uh,
I could not tell you where we played it at A&M or Austin.
I don't remember.
But I don't remember going home.
The only time I remember going home was the one time when Snake Tommy got caught and then Christmas.
And I didn't want to come back.
You mean you were thinking about dropping us?
Oh, yes, yes.
I told my mother that I was not going back.
And mother's response was, baby, you don't have to.
What led you to come back then?
He pointed out that old green 55 Studebaker and told me to get in it.
And he told me the way to A&M, and he said, you go, boy.
And so I did, you know.
And had it not been, I probably would have dropped out.
But my daddy told me that with tears in his eyes.
All right.
Then by the end of that semester, had you yet developed anybody that you turned to for sound advice, courses, major?
Charlie Ransdell, Mickey McGuire, anybody like that?
No, I never saw a dean.
Gosh, I hate to admit this.
I never saw a dean in my undergraduate career.
First dean I ever really sat down with was Fred Benson when I was in graduate school.
And he was almost a new dean himself at the time.
I never talked to one of the subdeans when I was in undergraduate school.
I never got on probation or anything, but I had to.
Well, who did you turn to to know what course to take?
Oh, goodness, Haskell.
We worked much closer back in those days with people like Austin Curley and some of those people over at the Counseling and Advising Center.
It seemed like maybe most of the counseling and advising was done by those people on what courses to take rather than your academic department.
I remember it that way.
That may not be exactly correct, but that's the way I remember it.
We sat down and there were some advisors.
in civil engineering that helped us finally work out a degree plan to make sure that we were following a degree plan and, you know, had the prerequisites and what have you.
By spring, you are a civil engineering major.
In the spring, I am signing up as a civil engineering major.
That's correct.
And what did you think
As you started looking at engineering, what did you think you were going to do?
Were you going to be a real engineer or were you going to be an academic?
I was going to be a real engineer at that time.
And I did not change that until my senior year.
I didn't really decide that I wanted to be an academic until I was a senior day in Hill.
Were you and your buddies aware of any easy courses when you were an undergraduate?
No, there were no such.
There were no such.
Even P.E.
was absolutely.
See, my first year, my fifth year, I couldn't swim very well.
And Art Adamson was the swimming guru.
They threw all of us in the old natatorium.
What was the name of it?
Whatever the name of the natatorium.
Downs.
Downs.
Downs Natatorium.
Downs Natatorium.
And everybody had to jump in and swim from one end to the other.
And if you couldn't swim from one end to the other, you had to take swimming and PE.
So my first semester, I took swimming.
And my second semester, I took an adaptive PE class, trying to build up some strength in the back and more heavy.
But those courses were miserable.
But no, there were no easy courses.
Gosh, I had, you know, you were not an easy prof in history.
I'm sorry.
I don't know if you just come out of rice and you felt like you had to be that way.
But I don't know.
I don't remember any easy.
I remember no easy classes at all at Texas A&M High School.
Y'all didn't hear about any giveaways for athletes?
No.
No, absolutely not.
The only courses that I knew of at that point where the grading was easy,
was Dan Russell, Dr. Dan the grade point man over in Rural Sociology.
There were a couple of courses where you could pass if you went to class.
If you went to class.
You might not get an A.
And they weren't just for athletes, they were for anybody.
No, we had a most difficult time.
Not only as a freshman, all through my undergraduate career.
In my junior and senior year, academically,
it got real tough in engineering because there were a lot of the athlete students, Air Force Institute of Technology students, old Korean veterans, both Army and Air Force.
It just flooded the campus.
And I would say at least a third of my civil engineering class were Army and Air Force officers.
And hey, man, they screwed the curve.
And they were serious.
Well, all they had to do was go to class and study and draw their pay.
And my late junior, senior year success, quite honestly, was tied to three or four of those guys.
Major Davis, Captain Eads, Captain Custer, Jack Custer from Rock Springs, Texas.
I never will forget those guys.
They let me study with them.
And my grades went up tremendously.
And then, of course, I married my senior year, and grades continued to go up.
But now, the spring of your freshman year, you're getting more serious, more sure you're going to stay in school.
Oh, yes.
All right, then you go, at the end of that first year, that summer, is that when your father died?
Yes.
All right, and so you're back home, and you stay with family through the fall.
Right.
And then come back.
Yes, I worked for the Texas Highway Department during that break.
What did that do to you or that family?
period out of school, what did that do to your determination about coming back to school?
Go back.
Go back.
Boy, there's something out there for you.
Working around those civil engineers at the highway department, go back.
There's something out there for you.
And I was very motivated to come back.
So you come back the spring of what, of your second year?
Yes.
You weren't in the Corps that semester?
No.
Where did you live?
Milder Hall.
Was there any teasing about your being a day duck?
Yeah, there was teasing about that, but I got through it, and then junior year went right back into the Corps.
Then after your sophomore year, what did you do that summer?
I worked for the highway department.
Okay.
And in that spring semester, I worked for TTI.
Spring semester, my sophomore year, I worked for TTI.
Was that a good maturing experience?
Oh, absolutely, yes, yes.
That led so much to what I eventually did, working for TTI and the state highway department.
And you said you had gotten in the singing cadets.
Describe that.
What was that like?
Oh, it was tremendous.
I had wanted to do it as a freshman and just didn't feel like I could do it.
Bob Boone was very new as the director of the singing cadets.
How did he and others receive a new singing cadet?

Well, being how I had already been on campus for a year or so, I didn't go through the typical buffoon type of situation that the other brand new freshman maybe had gone through, but I was a first tenor and Boone was so much in need of tenors that I think he would
Taking anyone who could squeak.
In fact, I was called Squeak.
That was my name.
And treated very, very fine.
Describe the routine for y'all.
Where did you practice and when?
We practiced in the bottom floor of, I guess it was Dorm 4.
Let me think, dorm two, dorm four, dorm three.
I believe it was dorm four, bottom floor, one end.
We had risers in an over-large room there, and that was the practice hall for the senior cadets every day, five days a week at five o'clock.
Five to six?
Uh-huh.
Did that also get you out of some bull in the corps?
See, I was civilian that first semester.
I was actually a civilian that semester.

And I don't know if you know it or not, but back in those days, there was kind of a compulsory corps, non-compulsory corps, and I don't remember exactly how that happened, but I was able to come in as a civilian that semester.
Went back into the corps, first semester of my junior year.
But yeah, even then, yeah, you were out of some bull.
Was there, to get into the singing cadets, was there any kind of... Audition.
Audition?
Yes.
And who...
Bob Boone.
Was it one-on-one?
Yes, and it was real unusual, Haskell.
I could not read music.
I had no music in high school and didn't come from a musically inclined family, although my sisters were all beautiful singers, and my dad was not bad.
My dad knew what a pitch pipe was, and we came from a...
a religious practice, I'm Church Christ, non-instrumental music.
And so Boone pulled out a few music pieces that I'd never seen before in my life and said, can you read music?
And I said, no, I can't.
And he says, well, what makes you think you can be a singing cadet?
I said, well, I think I can sing.
And he said, well, where have you sung before?
I said, well, I sing in church.
And he asked about piano accompaniment and what have you.
And I said, no, you know, it's all a cappella in Church of Christ.
So he says, OK. And he thumped through some music.
And he finally finds a religious piece that you can sing a cappella.
He said, well, let's do it.
And I think the lady that was at the time the pianist for the group maybe hit the starting key for it.
And I actually sang soprano lead on it, rather than a tenor part.
And I told him, I said, I can tell you right now, I cannot start the tenor lead on that and sing the tenor
on that song, and he said, well, I'll sing the soprano and you sing the tenor.
And we did.
And then he had the pianist play another piece, and Bob and I kind of played around on those, and I would pick up the tenor, and he said, yeah, I think you'll make a tenor for us.
And I think he had four first tenors, and the group was either 50 or 60.
I can't remember how many there were.
I think maybe it was 50 in those days.
And he only had four first tenors, and he said, I can really use a first tenor.
So I probably was selected as a singing cadet more because Bob needed one other voice than I really had the capability.
But I learned a little music in the process as I stayed in the cadets and thoroughly enjoyed it.
I really did.
Now, you stayed through?
Yes, I stayed through the rest of my academic career.
In general, the singing cadets in that era were made up of
Describe the typical.
About two-thirds corps, one-third civilian.
Most of them just enjoyed singing.
There were even a few athletes in the group, as a matter of fact.
Could you generalize that they were all Baptist, Methodist, church crazed?
No, I don't think so.
I think it was a pretty good mixture.
I know that when we went on spring tours, we typically paid visits to some of the big Methodist church and Baptist church in Houston and Fort Worth, Dallas and what have you.
No, there was no particular group represented in the cadets.
It was pretty diverse.
And your spring tour lasted how long?
A week, the biggest part of a week.
And you did something afternoon and evening?
Very common to do that, yeah, and then get on the bus and try to make it to the next place because, goodness, we'd go on a tour and we'd leave here.
And we'd go to El Paso on buses.
And we'd have concerts in Dallas, Fort Worth, Midland, Odessa, you know, El Paso, and then catch Waco on the way home or something.
It was jam-packed.
Any pranks or jokes?
among the scene cadets on these trips?
No, you know, I would have to say that the behavior and the overall demeanor of the scene cadets was a cut above, if you will, the behavior of everyone else in general.
I mean, Boone didn't put up with a lot of nonsense.
And see, we almost always were staying in the homes
of either old former students or church leaders and what have you.
We very seldom ever stayed in hotels.
The only time we ever stayed in hotels were, for example, Miss Teenage American Pageant or something like that.
All the rest of the time, we were staying in the home.
I never will forget staying in the home of T.M.
Smith.
I don't know if you remember the T.M.
Smith and T.L.
Smith.
They were big Aggies down in the West Columbia area, and I never will forget going to that part of the world.
Now, they're not
They're not the class of 99?
99 and 01 or something like that.
Really?
Oh, yes.
Yes, I stayed in Tim Smith's home.
All right, the reason my vibes start is that they were among the ardent opponents.
of co-education on compulsion.
You got it.
Alright, do you remember anything, hearing them talk about that?

No, I remember Mr. Smith showing us some oil wells, which he had several of, but what I remember most, Haskell, and it was so strange for a boy from the farm up in northeast Texas going to his home, and he had a maid and a butler.
And we were greeted at the front door by the butler.
And when I got ready to clean up for the concert, the butler helped me to the bath.
I mean, it was like, no, no, this is not really happening to Ned Walden, you know.
That was quite an experience.
And got ready to go.
to the concert, and typically what would happen is that whoever your host was would drive you to the concert.
Mr. Smith handed me the keys to a brand new Chrysler automobile.
It seemed like I remember it having 300 or 400 miles on it.
And after the concert, we would go to parties that the local people would host.
And there was a judge, and I could not tell you his name for anything, but this judge was hosting a party for the singing cadets.
And after the concert...
